With a handful of stones, she dammed the river. She created stagnant pools and deep reservoirs where the water slowed and thickened. She trapped the moments, forcing them to stay. This is why we are haunted by our pasts; we are the swimmers in the Weaver’s reservoirs, trading the blissful ignorance of the eternal present for the heavy, precious burden of remembering who we are.

