"Come to the surface," the Oxygen whispered through the cracks. "I will kiss you, and you will know the sky." The Silver clung to the bedrock, terrified that the air would dull its shine, turning its brilliance into black tarnish.

But in the dark, the Silver saw nothing but rock. It realized that a reflection requires light, and light requires exposure. It allowed the miners to pull it up. But to keep its shine in the air, it had to be trapped behind glass, cut off from the touch of the world. The Mirror is the Silver’s compromise: it is perfectly polished and sees everything, but it is forever separated from what it loves by a cold, invisible wall, reflecting a world it can never truly touch.

